We determined the COVID-19 severity according to the WHO classifications:
(1) mild, symptomatic COVID-19 patients without evidence of hypoxia or pneumonia;
(2) moderate, clinical signs of pneumonia (i.e., fever, cough, dyspnea, fast breathing) but not severe pneumonia, including blood oxygen saturation levels (SpO 2 ) ≥90% in room air; (3) severe, clinical signs of pneumonia plus one of the conditions as follows: respiratory rate >30 breaths/minute, severe respiratory distress, or SpO 2 <90% in room air and (4) critical, Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome, sepsis, or septic shock, other complications such as acute pulmonary embolism, acute coronary syndrome, acute stroke and delirium (Beeching, Fletcher & Fowler, 2019) .
